4 3. 5. The provisions of paragraphs 1 and 2 of this subsection
5 shall not apply to:
6 a. psychological, psychiatric, mental health, or
7 substance abuse treatment records. In the case of
8 psychological, psychiatric, mental health, or
9 substance abuse treatment records, access to
10 information contained in the records shall be obtained
11 pursuant to Section 1-109 of Title 43A of the Oklahoma
12 Statutes.
13 4. The provisions of paragraphs 1 and 2 of this subsection
14 shall not apply to, and
15 b. requests for medical records made by the Disability
16 Determination Division of the State Department of
17 Rehabilitation Services. The fee for such requests
18 shall be at a rate allowed by the Social Security
19 Administration.
20 B. 1. In cases involving a claim for personal injury or death
21 against any practitioner of the healing arts or a licensed hospital,
22 or a nursing facility or nursing home licensed pursuant to Section
23 1-1903 of Title 63 of the Oklahoma Statutes arising out of patient
24 care, where any person has placed the physical or mental condition
Req. No. 17479 Page 5

1 of t hat person in issue by the commencement of any action,
2 proceeding, or suit for damages, or where any person has placed in
3 issue the physical or mental condition of any other person or
4 deceased person by or through whom the person rightfully claims,
5 that person shall be deemed to waive any privilege granted by law
6 concerning any communication made to a physician or health care
7 provider with reference to any physical or mental condition or any
8 knowledge obtained by the physician or health care provider by
9 personal examination of the patient; provided that, before any
10 communication, medical or hospital record, or testimony is admitted
11 in evidence in any proceeding, it must be material and relevant to
12 an issue therein, according to existing rules of evidence.
13 Psychological, psychiatric, mental health, and substance abuse
14 treatment records and information from psychological, psychiatric,
15 mental health, and substance abuse treatment practitioners may only
16 be obtained provided the requirements of Section 1-109 of Title 43A
17 of the Oklahoma Statutes are met.
18 2. Any person who obtains any document pursuant to the
19 provisions of this section shall provide copies of the document to
20 any opposing party in the proceeding upon payment of the expense of
21 copying the document pursuant to the provisions of this section.
22 C. This section shall not apply to the records of an inmate in
23 a correctional institution when the correctional institution
24
Req. No. 17479 Page 6

1 beli eves the release of such information to be a threat to the
2 safety or security of the inmate or the institution.
3 D. 1. As used in this section, the terms “covered entity” and
4 “protected health information” shall have the same meaning as
5 provided under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability
6 Act of 1996 (HIPAA).
7 2. It shall be unlawful for a covered entity to use or disclose
8 protected health information except as authorized under HIPAA.
9 3. Intentional violation of paragraph 2 of this subsection
10 shall be deemed unprofessional conduct by the covered entity’s
11 licensure board or regulatory agency if applicable and subject to
12 mandatory license revocation.
13 4. If a covered entity believes a violation of paragraph 2 of
14 this subsection has occurred or will occur in relation to a request
15 for medical records, the covered entity may apply to a court of
16 competent jurisdiction for relief and the court shall award
17 appropriate relief including, but not limited to, temporary,
18 preliminary, or permanent injunctive relief.
19 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
